Umbral analysis of Thornwood focuses on what the substrate has produced: a site where concealment is architectural rather than chosen. The face-down oathbreaker burial tradition was the original concealment logic; the thorn-ring containment growth was the original exclusion infrastructure — the landscape implementing verdicts through growth rather than walls. The Root Covenant cult's reinterpretation of these practices, and the substrate's mediation of the necrotic ecology, produced a site where what is hidden (the dead's accumulated force, the crystal substrate's responsive capacity, the Wild Hunt's operational logic) constitutes the site's primary governing reality. The manorial surface — gates, titles, hereditary protocols — is the visible layer over an entirely hidden operating system. Thornwood demonstrates that concealment architectures built over responsive substrates do not stay concealed indefinitely. The binding failed because the concealment was never maintained — abandoned when the Harren family lost control and the Root Covenant filled the governance gap with doctrine rather than management.

